    questions:[
      {q:"Zimbabwe printed a $100 trillion dollar note during its 2008 economic crisis. What caused this catastrophic hyperinflation?", ch:["President Mugabe's land seizures from white farmers destroyed agricultural production; the government printed money to cover debt; inflation briefly reached 89.7 SEXTILLION percent (the highest ever recorded)","International sanctions entirely destroyed the economy","A series of natural disasters wiped out the entire economy","Regional war caused complete economic collapse"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
      {q:"Great Zimbabwe — which gave the country its name — is Africa's most impressive ancient stone structure. What is 'Zimbabwe' derived from?", ch:["Dzimba dza mabwe — 'houses of stone' in the Shona language — referring to the great stone enclosure complex built without mortar by the Shona kingdom (c. 1100–1450 AD)","A Ndebele word meaning 'land of gold'","A Zulu term for the high plateau","A Portuguese word for the plateau region"], a:0, cat:"🏛️ History"},
      {q:"The Great Zimbabwe was the capital of a powerful African empire. What was it famous for in its heyday (1200-1450 AD)?", ch:["It was the centre of a gold and ivory trade empire connecting inland Africa with Arab and Indian Ocean traders — at its peak housing 18,000 people, the largest city in sub-Saharan Africa","It was a purely religious site with no trading function","It was a military fortress never used as a city","It was built as a grain storage complex for the surrounding farms"], a:0, cat:"🏛️ History"},
      {q:"Robert Mugabe — Zimbabwe's first leader — is a complex historical figure. What was his role during independence?", ch:["He was a genuine independence hero who led ZANU-PF in the liberation war against white minority rule and Ian Smith; he initially governed with reconciliation, but later became authoritarian","He was appointed by Britain as a colonial administrator","He came to power in a military coup in 1980","He was elected in the first free elections with 99% of the vote legitimately"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
      {q:"Mugabe's Land Reform Programme of 2000 had devastating consequences. What happened?", ch:["White-owned commercial farms were seized and redistributed — but without training or resources for new farmers, agricultural production collapsed, causing food shortages and economic collapse","Land was successfully redistributed, tripling food production","International organisations carried out the redistribution smoothly","Only farms larger than 1,000 hectares were affected"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
      {q:"Victoria Falls is shared between Zimbabwe and Zambia. What is the local Shona name for the falls?", ch:["Mosi-oa-Tunya in Kololo language (the area's original people) — but the Shona call it 'Chimanimani' meaning 'spray'; it's UNESCO-listed and considered one of the Seven Natural Wonders of Africa","Nyanga — meaning great water","Nyaminyami — named after the Zambezi river god","Chimanimani — same as Zimbabwe's eastern mountains"], a:0, cat:"🌊 Nature"},
      {q:"Zimbabwe has 16 official languages — the most in Africa. What are the main ones?", ch:["Shona, Ndebele, and English — these three are the most widely used; Shona is spoken by about 70% and Ndebele by about 20% of the population","English and Shona only","Shona, Ndebele, Tonga, and Venda are equal","Only Shona is truly national — others are regional"], a:0, cat:"🗣️ Culture"},
      {q:"The Zimbabwe Bird — the national emblem on the flag — is a soapstone carving of an eagle. Where was the original found?", ch:["At Great Zimbabwe ruins — eight soapstone birds were found there; they represent the Bateleur Eagle and are believed to be 15th century royal symbols; the symbol was so powerful Rhodesia also used it","In the Zimbabwean highlands","In a Victoria Falls archaeological site","In the National Museum of Harare"], a:0, cat:"🦅 Culture"},
      {q:"Emmerson Mnangagwa — nicknamed 'The Crocodile' — became president in 2017. How?", ch:["He orchestrated a military coup against his former mentor Robert Mugabe — ending Mugabe's 37-year rule; the army placed Mugabe under house arrest and he resigned; Mnangagwa took power","He won a democratic election beating Mugabe","He was appointed by the ZANU-PF party after Mugabe voluntarily retired","He led a popular revolution that overthrew Mugabe"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
      {q:"Zimbabwe's Hwange National Park is one of Africa's great wildlife reserves. What animal is found there in extraordinary numbers?", ch:["African elephants — Hwange has one of Africa's largest elephant populations, estimated at 45,000–50,000; the elephants are so numerous they are considered overpopulated","Mountain gorillas","Black rhinoceros in record numbers","Wild dogs — the largest pack in Africa"], a:0, cat:"🐘 Nature"},
      {q:"Morgan Tsvangirai — Zimbabwe's most important opposition leader — led which political party against Mugabe?", ch:["Movement for Democratic Change (MDC) — founded in 1999 from trade union movements; Tsvangirai actually won more votes than Mugabe in 2008 but was violently prevented from taking office","Zimbabwe Liberation Front","National Democratic Party","ZAPU (Zimbabwe African People's Union)"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
      {q:"The Matobo Hills in southern Zimbabwe are a UNESCO World Heritage site containing ancient rock art. What historical figure is buried there?", ch:["Cecil Rhodes — the British imperialist who colonised Rhodesia is buried in the Matobo Hills at his own request, next to his friend Leander Starr Jameson","Robert Mugabe — buried with full state honours","Joshua Nkomo — ZAPU leader and Zimbabwe's 'Father Zimbabwe'","David Livingstone — the explorer who mapped the region"], a:0, cat:"📜 History"},
    ],
